Vector Databases: The Complete Guide (2024) ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐ 4.8/5 (247 reviews)

Posted by admin on March 15, 2024 | Updated: Oct 1, 2024 | 12 min read | 💬 89 comments

So you want to build a RAG system? Well you're in luck because vector databases are HOT right now!! 🔥 Everyone's talking about them...

What even IS a vector database anyway???

Basically it stores your text as numbers (vectors) so you can do semantic search. Think of it like Google but for your own documents. Instead of exact word matching it understands MEANING.

TOP VECTOR DB OPTIONS 2024:
▶ Pinecone - $$$ but works great
▶ Qdrant - open source, rust-based (FAST!)  
▶ Weaviate - lots of features, kinda complex
▶ Chroma - perfect for development/testing
▶ PostgreSQL pgvector - surprisingly good!

🚨 BREAKING: New OpenAI embedding models just dropped! ada-002 is being deprecated... 

Real talk: I've been working with vector DBs for 2+ years and here's what I learned the hard way...

Most tutorials are BS. They use perfect markdown documents but real data is MESSY AF. Think scraped web pages, PDFs with weird formatting, email dumps, chat logs, etc.

Pro tip: Spend more time on data cleaning than model tuning. Garbage in = garbage out.

Title: Spent 6 months building RAG system, learned some hard truths

So I just finished deploying our company's internal RAG system (10k+ documents, mostly technical specs and emails). Thought I'd share what worked and what didn't...

WHAT WORKED:
✅ Multi-query retrieval (game changer!)
✅ Hybrid search (BM25 + vector)
✅ Simple chunking with overlap
✅ PostgreSQL pgvector (way cheaper than Pinecone)

WHAT DIDN'T WORK:
❌ Self-querying (requires perfect metadata - we don't have that)
❌ Complex retrieval chains (too many failure points)  
❌ Fancy reranking models (marginal improvement, adds latency)
❌ Trying to parse every document type (some PDFs are just garbage)

Key insight: Focus on data quality over algorithm complexity. We spent weeks optimizing retrieval when the real issue was crappy OCR from scanned documents.

Our stack: LangChain + pgvector + Ollama (local deployment for privacy)

AMA about production RAG systems!

RAG System Implementation - Project Falcon

Last updated: Sept 15, 2024 by David Chen

Status: LIVE IN PRODUCTION

After 8 months of development, our RAG system is finally deployed! Here's what we learned...

Technology Stack:

  • Vector DB: Qdrant (running on k8s cluster)
  • Embeddings: OpenAI ada-002 → Switched to Ollama nomic-embed-text (cost savings)
  • LLM: GPT-4 → Switched to local Llama3 (privacy requirements)
  • Framework: LangChain (love/hate relationship)

Pain Points:

  1. Data Quality: Our documents are a mess. PDFs with weird encoding, Word docs with tables that don't parse properly, scanned images with terrible OCR...
  2. Chunking Strategy: Tried 10 different approaches. Settled on 500 chars with 50 char overlap. Not perfect but good enough.
  3. Metadata Extraction: Originally planned fancy auto-tagging. Reality: most docs don't have useful metadata. Now we just use filename + date.
• Performance: First version took 45 seconds per query. Current version: ~3-4 seconds. Still not great but acceptable.

What Actually Works:

Multi-query retrieval is AMAZING. Instead of searching once, generate 3-5 variations of the query and combine results. Huge improvement in recall.

Parent-document retrieval helps too. Search on small chunks but return larger context. Users need more context than just the matching sentence.

AVOID: Self-querying retrieval. Sounds great in theory but requires high-quality metadata which we don't have. Spent 3 weeks on it and threw it away.

Lessons Learned:

❌ Don't optimize prematurely
❌ Don't trust academic benchmarks
❌ Don't assume your data is clean
✅ Start simple and iterate
✅ Focus on user experience over technical elegance
✅ Test with real users early and often

Next phase: Add hybrid search (keyword + vector) and better result ranking.

- ef_construct: Search width during construction (100-800)
- ef: Search width during query (higher = better accuracy, slower search)
